The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Chennai, Aug. 13 (PTI): A 24-year-old woman, whose marriage was not consummated even after a year, has sought divorce and a permanent alimony of Rs 1 crore.          
	The woman, who claimed she quit her software job on insistence by her in-laws, charged them with hiding the fact that their son suffered from some hereditary sexual problem and was incapable of fulfilling his conjugal responsibilities and was impotent.           
	She claimed her husband kept a distance from her and his parents also slept in the same room for some time. The woman said her parents had spent over Rs 11 lakh on the marriage, besides giving 30 sovereign gold jewellery, silver articles and household items. The woman alleged she was also subjected to dowry harassment.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Four students of Jawaharlal Nehru University have been caught by authorities while they were allegedly ragging a junior on the campus. The accused, all second-year MCA students, have been told to leave the hostel till a campus probe is done.                   
	 Ahmedabad: Gujarat police have claimed to have arrested the kingpin of a fake currency racket who allegedly had links with Pakistani intelligence agencies. Asgar Ali, from Godhra who acquired Indian, Bangladeshi and Pakistani passports, was picked up on Wednesday night with Rs 1.35 lakh of fake notes.                   
	 Lucknow: Uttar Pradesh police have registered cheating cases against 15 state officials whom the Mayavati government had suspended for selling land in Greater Noida at throwaway prices to hotel owners. Four officials are from the IAS cadre. One of the officials has retired.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Centre has extended the visa of Bangladeshi writer Taslima Nasreen for six months till next February 16. Her visa would have expired on August 17. The writer, who was asked to leave India last March, had sought extension of the visa.                                                                                                                           
